We show in Figure {\ref{fig:fig15}} the relative difference between theoretical angular correlations, computed by using Equation (\ref{eq:wtheta}), when we used the training set $n(z)$ (red line in Figure \ref{fig:fig2}) and the mean $n(z)$ of ten different random samples extracted from the catalogue with the same number of galaxies as the training set, which is similar to the blue solid line in Figure \ref{fig:fig2}.  We found relative differences smaller than $2\%$ over the redshift range for all angles, $0.1<\theta<1$. This implies a relative difference smaller than $1\%$ for the galaxy bias, which is lower than the differences observed for our different photo-z statistics. 

